label chapter17:

    # [Scene: Saltgarden Research Lab | Dusk]

    scene bg ch15_3be532_1 at full_bg
    # play music "music_placeholder"  # [Music: Low, aching piano with sparse strings]
    # play sound "sfx_placeholder"  # [Sound: Distant gulls; the lab's dehumidifier hissing; the soft clack of a camera shutter]
    "You remember the surge of triumph — the first shipment of Hearthbend kits stacked like a promise in the back alley of the lab, the apprentices' laughter when their paychecks arrived on time, the way the"
    "community garden hummed with new hands learning to bind eelgrass to frames. The grant read like a lifeline. You traced its clauses with the same careful hand you use on cartographic margins, convinced you could mark"
    "out safe space within its lines."
    "Now those same margins are a ledger of nicked corners and footnotes that smell faintly of printer ink and courtrooms. Your notebook sits open on the workbench beside Ilias Navarro's tide-watch bracelet, pages threaded with memos"
    "and photographs: logos placed where a thankful credit should have been, redlines that replace 'open license' with 'licensed use.' Your handwriting tilts downward where your pen caught on the word 'royalty.'"
    show maya_kestrel at left:
        zoom 0.7

    maya_kestrel "We built this to be shared — to keep communities from having to invent the wheel again. That was the whole point."
    show ilias_navarro at right:
        zoom 0.7

    ilias_navarro "I know. We did it right. We really did.' (He sinks onto a lab stool, fingers tracing a damp ring on the table.) 'But look — look at what the grant's legal team did. They took the schematic and wrote their brand across it. They bundled the apprentices into contract terms that read like quotas."
    "He says the words as if naming something can fix it. You hear the fatigue under his voice, the same tired optimism that once made you both laugh in the rain. You want to be harsher;"
    "you want to spit out accusations that would scar them as deep as they've scarred you. Instead you fold the edges of the photograph of a community member teaching a child to weave kelp, like you"
    "are smoothing the memory so it won't crack."

    ilias_navarro "What if I take a role with them? I get a seat at the table where they make the scale decisions. I could steer the deployments, try to keep the rent clauses out, protect apprentices—"
    "The possibility is a rope thrown from a cliff: plausible, dangerous. You know why he says it. You know why his chest tightens when he imagines standing inside the corporate rooms, translating ethics into line items."
    "You also know what it means for Hearthbend if he leaves — for the hands that learned at Saltgarden, for Etta when her dock sits half-empty, for the market's fragile web."

    maya_kestrel "You think they won't use you. They'll use your name like a seal and keep the clauses.' (There is no anger left in your voice; only the dry ache that comes after hope has been folded flat.) 'If you go, what happens when they start pricing our apprenticeships back at the town as 'franchise fees'?"

    ilias_navarro "Then I go with a list. I go with our prototypes and our counter-proposals. I go because staying here while they repurpose us feels like watching a tide take a house apart, and not trying to reach it."
    "He says it with that clumsy, heartfelt bravery that has always been his — a choice to act rather than to be acted upon. You should be proud. You should be steadied by the courage of"
    "a friend who won't let the ship drift without anchors. Instead you feel the pendant at your throat suddenly heavy, a small carved coral pressing cold against your sternum like something you could bury in the"
    "wet mud and forget."

    menu:
        "Tell him to refuse the offer":
            "You say the words first, sharp and immediate: 'Don't go.' They land like pebbles and you watch the ripple. Ilias flinches but holds your gaze. 'If you stay,' you add, 'we'll make a better case together.' He smiles, grateful and frightened."
        "Let him go, quietly":
            "You force a smile that doesn't reach your eyes. 'If you think you can influence them, then go.' Your voice is small in the lab's damp air. Ilias nods, a goodbye that isn't spoken aloud."

    # --- merge ---
    "Continue"
    # [Scene: Harborfront Market | Morning]
    hide maya_kestrel
    hide ilias_navarro

    scene bg ch15_3be532_2 at full_bg
    # play music "music_placeholder"  # [Music: A dull brass lament threaded with a single violin]
    # play sound "sfx_placeholder"  # [Sound: Market clamor muted by a low, steady sea; the soft slap of a brochure in the wind]
    "The market is where the town announces its health to itself. Today the announcement is foreign. The glossy paper reflects sunlight like a surfacing fin: images of smiling crews in branded vests, before-and-after shots that have"
    "been cropped to exclude the patched roofs, an investor quote praising 'replicable labor models.' You know those faces; you know those hands — but someone else has set a frame over them."
    "Rafi Soto approaches, camera swinging from his shoulder with the casual rhythm you've known since childhood. His grin is smaller than usual. The camera's strap digs into his paint-splattered jacket; there's an editorial weight to the way he clears his throat."
    show rafi_soto at left:
        zoom 0.7

    rafi_soto "The piece took a different turn,' he says without preamble. 'At first people loved it — a feel-good thing. Then the editor bumped it with the investor's angle. I—' (He rubs at the back of his neck.) 'I tried to push back."
    show maya_kestrel at right:
        zoom 0.7

    maya_kestrel "You wrote it,' you say. 'You wrote the part about apprenticeships being community-owned."

    rafi_soto "I did. Then they ran an op-ed that—' (He swallows.) '—that called it 'a scalable labor solution.' They used our photos."
    "You think of the elderly hands that taught knotwork in a community hall and the apprentice who used those hands to stitch a living. The phrase 'scalable labor solution' sounds like a place where people become inputs rather than neighbors."

    maya_kestrel "What did you say?"

    rafi_soto "I wrote a follow-up. A different tone. I dug into the contracts. The piece is live — it's not celebratory anymore. It called out the rent clauses, the franchise language. The editor gave me grief, but readers are calling them on it. People are furious."
    "You feel the motion of the town shifting beneath the same tide. There is anger. There is righteous betrayal. But anger is not always enough to undo contracts signed with lawyers who drink better coffee than you ever will."

    menu:
        "Stand with Rafi publicly":
            "You clap a hand on his shoulder and say, 'I'll stand with you at the town square.' His face opens like a shutter. He promises to post your statement. People gather slowly, murmuring and then raising their voices."
        "Work behind the scenes":
            "You keep your voice low. 'Let me see the drafts. We can build a legal narrative that can't be dismissed.' Rafi nods; you both duck into a booth to draft something more precise."

