    # [Scene: Etta Muir's Dock | Afternoon]
    hide rafi_soto
    hide maya_kestrel

    scene bg ch15_3be532_3 at full_bg
    # play music "music_placeholder"  # [Music: Sparse, mournful woodwinds]
    # play sound "sfx_placeholder"  # [Sound: The creak of piling, a slow lap of waves, the distant call of a market vendor]
    "Etta's hands are the map of Hearthbend — callused, laced with salt lines, the knuckles like small stones. She stands at the edge of her dock with two cardboard boxes. The scent of smoked fish and"
    "oilskin wraps around her like a shawl. Her hair is a silver knot; she has the tired steadiness of someone who has watched the weather change and learned to keep making bowls of bread."
    show etta_muir at left:
        zoom 0.7

    etta_muir "They offered a little,' she says. 'For the dock. A sum that could keep me comfortable for a spell."
    show maya_kestrel at right:
        zoom 0.7

    maya_kestrel "Etta—' You don't know the sequence of sentences that could make this right. There isn't one. Your throat is a dry shell. 'Why sell it?"

    etta_muir "Because I won't take rent that comes with strings. I won't be told when and how I can fish for a living by a company that puts 'efficiency' over people. I won't have them call my grandchildren 'labor credits.'"
    "Her jaw tightens. The cardboard boxes hold a few small things: a carved spool of twine, an old brass lighter, a photograph of a younger Etta and a man leaning on a pier. You reach out and touch the boat's paint, felt-smooth from years of hands."

    etta_muir "I have friends who need help buying boats, Maya. I can send them money. But I'm not staying to watch our water turned into ordinance and schedules. If this was meant to keep people safe and in place, then why does it start with renting out their ability to breathe?"

    maya_kestrel "Is there anything I can—"
    "Etta looks at you like she's reading the map of a life you both tried to draw. The look is not unkind. It is the exact sort of disappointment that consolidates into a decision."

    etta_muir "Take the petition, child,' she says. 'Take the signatures while I find a place where no one will measure me in quotas."
    "She hands you a folded paper. It is a small, stubborn thing in your palm: names in ink, the looped handwriting of neighbors. You fold it into your notebook like a pressed leaf."

    menu:
        "Promise to fight the appropriation publicly":
            "You hold Etta's hand and promise: 'We'll expose what they did. We'll make it impossible to whitewash our method.' She nods slowly, the gesture a fragile pact."
        "Offer personal help instead of public confrontation":
            "You say you'll help her find a buyer who won't turn the dock into a rental. She accepts the offer like a quiet balm, grateful but not convinced."

